---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Privacy Learning Center — Journal Foundation"
  description="Understand digital privacy, security, and sovereignty with plain-language guides from Journal Foundation."
>
  <div class="learn container">
    <header class="learn__hero">
      <h1>Privacy Learning Center</h1>
      <p class="lead">Understand digital privacy, security, and sovereignty—whether or not you ever use our protocols.</p>
      <p>
        Journal Foundation believes literacy is a prerequisite to freedom. This center distills the core ideas behind our work
        and offers practical guides you can use today.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Why Privacy Matters</h2>
      <p>
        Surveillance capitalism profits from predicting and influencing human behavior. Platforms harvest every click, pause,
        and conversation. Metadata about who you talk to, when you're active, and what communities you join is weaponized for
        manipulation and control.
      </p>
      <p>
        Privacy is not secrecy—it's the right to decide who sees your life. When you lose that right, algorithms shape what you
        believe, who you trust, and how you vote.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Essential Concepts</h2>

      <article class="concept">
        <h3>What Is Metadata?</h3>
        <p>
          Metadata is data about data—timestamps, IP addresses, location, who messaged whom. It's the pattern that reveals the
          story even when the content stays encrypted.
        </p>
        <p class="example">Example: A messaging app might hide the text of your conversation but still know every person you talk to and when.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="concept">
        <h3>What Is End-to-End Encryption?</h3>
        <p>
          End-to-end encryption (E2EE) ensures only the sender and receiver can read the content. Apps like Signal and WhatsApp
          use E2EE so servers can't see message bodies.
        </p>
        <p>
          E2EE does <em>not</em> hide metadata. Phone numbers, contact lists, and message timing still leak information unless
          additional protections exist.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="concept">
        <h3>What Is Decentralization?</h3>
        <p>
          Decentralized systems distribute infrastructure across many operators instead of a single company. Examples include
          Mastodon and the wider Fediverse.
        </p>
        <p>
          Decentralization alone doesn't guarantee privacy. Server admins often see user data, and metadata remains exposed to
          surveillance.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="concept">
        <h3>What Is Anonymization?</h3>
        <p>
          Anonymization reduces the metadata that links digital actions back to real people. It focuses on traffic analysis,
          capability-scoped sharing, and minimizing what observers can learn.
        </p>
        <p>
          Without anonymization, decentralized systems still enable mass profiling and retroactive surveillance.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Practical Guides</h2>
      <ul class="guide-list">
        <li>How to evaluate a "privacy-focused" app</li>
        <li>How to read a privacy policy</li>
        <li>How to enable Global Privacy Control</li>
        <li>How to use Signal safely</li>
        <li>How to understand app permissions</li>
        <li>How to protect yourself from surveillance</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Advanced Topics</h2>
      <ul class="guide-list">
        <li>Understanding threat models</li>
        <li>The China problem (quantum + bulk seizure)</li>
        <li>Why "I have nothing to hide" is wrong</li>
        <li>How influence works at scale</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These explorations inform why the Journal Protocol Stack prioritizes anonymization and custody. Learn how the stack fits
        together on the <a href="/stack">Stack page</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Resources</h2>
      <ul class="guide-list">
        <li><a href="/whitepapers">Journal Foundation whitepapers</a></li>
        <li><a href="/stack">The Journal Protocol Stack</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.eff.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Electronic Frontier Foundation</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.torproject.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tor Project</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://ssd.eff.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Surveillance Self-Defense Guide</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .learn {
    margin: var(--space-3xl) auto var(--space-4xl);
  }

  .learn__hero {
    max-width: 72ch;
    margin: 0 auto var(--space-3xl);
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .section {
    max-width: 72ch;
    margin: 0 auto var(--space-2xl);
  }

  .concept {
    background: var(--void-lighter);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--space-xl) var(--space-lg);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .concept h3 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .example {
    background: rgba(45, 125, 255, 0.12);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--electric-blue);
    padding: var(--space-sm) var(--space-md);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }

  .guide-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-lg) 0;
  }

  .guide-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-lg);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .guide-list li::before {
    content: "→";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--electric-blue);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .learn {
      margin-top: var(--space-2xl);
    }
  }
</style>
